"""The MCP tool catalog — the agent-facing prompt copy, separated from the wiring.

`_CATALOG` is the registry of `(group, name, fn, description, json_schema)` tuples
that the MCP server advertises to a coding agent; the descriptions and schemas here
are effectively prompt text the agent reads, so they're worth keeping in one place
apart from the ~50 thin tool implementations (those live in `mcp_tools`).

**Names are domain-namespaced** (`<domain>_<verb>_<object>`) so an agent can route
to the right tool from the *name alone*, without paying a schema fetch — the name is
the only zero-token signal under deferred (name-only) tool loading. The domains:
`proj` (projects) · `target` (target lifecycle + every target-creator, incl. rehost)
· `re` (static reverse engineering) · `fs` (a target's unpacked filesystem) · `obs`
(the Observation store) · `graph` (the curated node/edge/hypothesis graph) · `finding`
(findings, n-day, proving) · `src` (source trees + builds) · `fuzz` (campaigns) ·
`net` (live network interaction + egress) · `task` (the task runner) · `meta`
(schemas + health). The advertised *name* is what changed; the underlying `mcp_tools`
functions keep their original names.

**Closed value-sets are real `enum`s, sourced from the codebase's own definitions**
(`NodeType`/`EdgeType`/`SOCKET_KINDS`/annotation kinds/Finding Literals/…), so the
agent can't pass a node/edge/finding type the engine doesn't understand, and the lists
never drift from `meta_get_schemas` — adding a `NodeType` member updates both at once
(the String columns keep zero-migration; the enum just mirrors the current vocab).

The dependency is strictly one-way: this module imports the tool functions from
`mcp_tools`; `mcp_tools` re-exports `GROUPS`/`catalog` from here for back-compat, but
never the other way around — so there is no import cycle.
"""

from __future__ import annotations

