    ("read", "re_binutils_facts", _t.binutils_facts, "Authoritative low-level ELF facts via GNU binutils (nm/objdump/readelf/strings) run in the sandbox: the symbol table, dynamic imports/exports, relocations (incl. PLT jump-slot imports), sections, ELF/program headers, and the security mitigations (NX, RELRO, PIE, stack canary, FORTIFY) — the fast first-minute facts pass, sharper than target_facts/re_imports (recon caps imports/strings). QUERY: records a binutils_facts Observation and tags is_sink on any dangerous import ALREADY in the graph + folds the mitigation flags onto the target; adds NO new graph nodes — promote what matters. Check obs_list(target_id) first to reuse a prior pass.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "re_list_strings", _t.list_strings, "GREP a target's FULL string table (the real strings(1) pass over the binary, NOT a small recon sample) for a substring `pattern` — hardcoded creds, URLs, format strings (%s), command templates (.cgi), config keys (factory/aes) anywhere in the binary. Server-side filtered + PAGINATED: pass `pattern` to filter, `offset`/`limit` to page (default 200, max 1000); the result reports the total match count + the next offset to page on (no obs_get dance). With no `pattern` it lists the table page by page. QUERY: records an Observation; adds no graph nodes. Falls back to the ~40-entry recon sample (flagged in the result) ONLY when the full strings pass is unavailable — a non-ELF artifact or the sandbox image being down. For OBFUSCATED stack/decoded strings a plain pass misses (PE/x86 only), use re_floss_strings.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "pattern": {"type": "string", "description": "substring to grep the full string table for"}, "offset": {"type": "integer", "description": "page start index into the matches (default 0)"}, "limit": {"type": "integer", "description": "max strings to return (default 200, clamped 1–1000)"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "re_floss_strings", _t.floss_strings, "Recover OBFUSCATED strings a plain re_list_strings pass MISSES — STACK strings (built byte-by-byte on the stack at runtime), TIGHT strings, and DECODED strings (produced by a decode routine FLOSS lightly EMULATES in the sandbox) — via FLARE FLOSS. On firmware/malware these hidden strings (URLs, command templates, keys, format strings) are often the lead. QUERY: records a floss_strings Observation; adds NO graph nodes — PROMOTE an interesting recovered string to a string node deliberately (graph_create_node node_type=string). FLOSS is slow, so check obs_list(target_id) first to reuse a prior pass. NOTE: stack/tight/decoded recovery is x86/amd64 PE ONLY — an INHERENT vivisect/FLOSS limitation, not a bug; on an ELF/foreign-arch artifact (most firmware) it degrades to a static-strings pass (equivalent to a plain strings) with a note, so don't expect hidden-string recovery on firmware — use re_list_strings to grep the static table there. Always-on static tool (no gate — FLOSS emulates decode routines in-process and never executes the target, so it relaxes no boundary); slower than re_list_strings, hence the obs_list reuse check above.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "min_length": {"type": "integer", "description": "min string length (default 4, clamped 4–64)"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "re_yara_scan", _t.yara_scan, "Match ONE target's bytes against YARA rules (the bundled high-signal set — embedded creds, known-bad library banners, weak-crypto constants, packer signatures — plus any .yar the user dropped in the HEXGRAPH_HOME rules dir), run in the sandbox. PROMOTE: each matched rule becomes a project-level `pattern` node + a `matches_rule` edge from this target, carrying the rule's DECLARED severity/cve (the matcher never fabricates a severity or auto-mints a finding — promote a match to a finding deliberately). Records a yara_matches Observation; check obs_list(target_id, kind='yara_matches') first to reuse a prior pass. `ruleset` (a bundled ruleset id, or 'all', default 'all') is the only knob — never a yara command line. The pattern complement to the exact-hash n-day link finding_link_same_code. For the WHOLE project (every target + extracted firmware file) use re_yara_sweep. Always-on static tool (no gate — a static MATCH reads bytes and never executes, so it relaxes no boundary); drop your own .yar rules in the HEXGRAPH_HOME rules dir.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "ruleset": {"type": "string", "description": "bundled ruleset id, or 'all' (default)"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("write", "re_yara_sweep", _t.yara_sweep, "Project-wide YARA sweep — the PATTERN n-day complement to finding_link_same_code (exact hash): match every non-archived byte target AND every extracted firmware file against the bundled high-signal rules (+ any user .yar in the HEXGRAPH_HOME rules dir), recording a yara_matches Observation per artifact and promoting matched rules to shared project-level `pattern` nodes via `matches_rule` edges (so the graph shows which targets/files a rule matched). One analyst's rule → a corpus-wide hunt. `ruleset` is a bundled ruleset id (or 'all', default). The matcher carries each rule's DECLARED severity/cve onto the pattern node but never fabricates a severity or auto-mints a finding — promote a hit to a finding deliberately. Returns a roll-up of scanned/match/promotion counts + hits. Always-on static tool (no gate — a static MATCH relaxes no boundary).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "ruleset": {"type": "string", "description": "bundled ruleset id, or 'all' (default)"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("run", "re_solve_reaching_input", _t.solve_reaching_input, "SOLVE for a concrete input that DRIVES execution to a sink (e.g. system/execve/strcpy) via angr SYMBOLIC EXECUTION in the dedicated angr sandbox image — the strongest STATIC claim short of a live PoC, because it produces a concrete REACHING INPUT (often raw non-ASCII bytes a guess can't hit). You REQUEST it with a sink selector — you never write an angr script; HexGraph runs the bounded, deterministic solve (DFS + wall-clock/step/state caps). PROMOTE: on success it promotes the grounded path (the sink as an is_sink node + the enclosing function + a `calls` edge) and emits a high-confidence `vulnerability` finding whose evidence.reproducer is the solved input (hex), assurance input_reachable/static; records a `solver` Observation either way. `sink_func` (the dangerous callee to reach, e.g. 'system') is the main knob; optionally `function` (the enclosing routine) and `budget`. angr is HEAVY + slow — check obs_list(target_id, kind='solver') first to reuse a prior solve. Returns cleanly unsolved when no reaching input exists within the budget (nothing fabricated). Gated: features.angr (symbolic execution; relaxes no sandbox/exec/egress boundary — it explores bytes, never runs the target — but heavy, so policy-gated like emulation).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "sink_func": {"type": "string", "description": "the dangerous callee to reach, e.g. 'system'"}, "function": {"type": "string", "description": "optional enclosing routine"}, "budget": {"type": "string", "enum": ["quick", "default", "deep"]}}, "required": ["target_id", "sink_func"]}),
    ("run", "re_solve_constraint", _t.solve_constraint, "Recover the VALUE/input that SATISFIES a single check (the secret a strcmp compares against, the serial a license gate validates) via angr — the symbolic-execution analogue of re_recover_constant (which emulates a self-contained routine). You give a check selector; HexGraph runs the bounded solve in the angr image. ENRICH: on success annotates the function node with the recovered value (attrs.recovered_value / satisfying_input_hex) and records a `solver` Observation; adds no new graph nodes. Single-check solving ONLY — NOT whole-program exploration. `function` names the routine; optionally `check_addr` pins the pass/success block, or `sink_func` when the check gates a sink and you don't know the pass block; `budget` is quick|default|deep. Gated: features.angr (heavy, policy-gated like emulation; relaxes no boundary).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "function": {"type": "string"}, "check_addr": {"type": "string"}, "sink_func": {"type": "string"}, "budget": {"type": "string", "enum": ["quick", "default", "deep"]}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "re_xrefs", _t.xrefs, "Cross-references: which functions CALL a symbol/sink and where (omit `symbol` to map dangerous sinks, format-string sinks, AND network/socket surface bind/listen/connect/recv). Trace a sink back to its caller, or find listen/connect sites to model as socket nodes. QUERY: records an Observation and tags is_sink on any dangerous-import symbol ALREADY in the graph; adds no new graph nodes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "symbol": {"type": "string", "description": "sink/symbol name; omit to map ALL dangerous + format + network sinks"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "re_call_graph", _t.call_graph, "The target's CALL GRAPH (who-calls-whom across the program), or — with a `function` — the neighbourhood rooted at it out to `depth` (default 2). Returns the whole-program graph, falling back to the recon-computed graph in the Observation store when the probe path comes up empty (so you see the structure without promoting functions one by one). QUERY: records a call_graph Observation that also SELF-WIRES `calls` edges among functions ALREADY in the graph (promote functions to curate the wired graph); creates no new nodes. Use to see the program's structure / a function's reachable callees without decompiling each.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "function": {"type": "string", "description": "optional root; omit for the whole-program graph"}, "depth": {"type": "integer", "description": "neighbourhood radius around `function` (default 2)"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "re_function_xrefs", _t.function_xrefs, "Both directions for ONE function: its CALLERS (who calls it) AND its CALLEES (what it calls) — walk the call graph around a function of interest (the bidirectional complement to re_xrefs, which is callers-of-a-sink only). QUERY: records an Observation; adds no graph nodes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "function": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["target_id", "function"]}),
    ("read", "re_data_xrefs", _t.data_xrefs, "Cross-references TO a hex ADDRESS (or a symbol/label that resolves to one) — every code/data/string reference that points at it (who reads/writes/points to this datum or string constant). Use after re_list_strings/decompile surfaces an interesting address to find who touches it. QUERY: records an Observation; adds no graph nodes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "address": {"type": "string", "description": "hex address, or a symbol/label that resolves to one"}}, "required": ["target_id", "address"]}),
    ("read", "re_search_decompiled", _t.search_decompiled, "Search ACROSS already-decompiled function BODIES on a target for a string/identifier (a variable/constant/call/format string) — mines PRIOR decompilations in the Observation store (NO re-decompile), returns the matching functions + a snippet. Pair with re_decompile_function: decompile candidates first, then grep their bodies here. QUERY: records an Observation; adds no graph nodes. A long hit list is truncated to max_chars with a marker naming both recovery paths (re-call with a bigger max_chars, or obs_get for the full payload).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "query": {"type": "string", "description": "substring/identifier to grep across decompiled bodies"}, "max_chars": {"type": "integer", "description": _MAX_CHARS_DESC}}, "required": ["target_id", "query"]}),

    # ---- fs: a target's unpacked filesystem -----------------------------------------
    ("read", "fs_list", _t.list_filesystem, "List a firmware target's unpacked filesystem (paths/sizes/which are ELFs or already child targets) — find config files, scripts, keys, web assets to read with fs_read_file (or promote a binary with target_promote_file). PAGINATED + filterable for big firmware (a real image unpacks to hundreds-to-thousands of files; an unfiltered dump overflows context): `path_prefix` scopes to a directory (e.g. 'usr/sbin'), `elf_only=true` lists only binaries, `offset`/`limit` page (default 200, max 2000). The result reports `total` + `next_offset` so you can page the rest. Returns {unpacked, method, files:[{rel,size,is_elf,added,revealed,child_target_id}], total, offset, next_offset, has_more}.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "path_prefix": {"type": "string", "description": "list only entries whose path starts with this (e.g. 'usr/sbin')"}, "elf_only": {"type": "boolean", "description": "list only ELF binaries (find daemons/CGIs to promote)"}, "offset": {"type": "integer", "description": "page start index into the (filtered) list (default 0)"}, "limit": {"type": "integer", "description": "max entries to return (default 200, clamped 1–2000)"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "fs_read_file", _t.read_file, "Read ONE file from a firmware target's unpacked filesystem (config/script/key/web template — NOT the raw binary; use re_decompile_function for code). Bounded 256 KiB, path-traversal safe; text as-is, binary as hex. `path` is relative to the extracted root (see fs_list).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "path": {"type": "string", "description": "file path relative to the extracted root (see fs_list)"}}, "required": ["target_id", "path"]}),

    # ---- obs: the Observation store -------------------------------------------------
    ("read", "obs_list", _t.list_observations, "Prior deterministic analysis on a target — the OBSERVATION STORE (the substrate, NOT the curated graph): decompilations, function lists, xrefs, taint, strings, structs, each recorded once as a reusable Observation. Returns row metadata newest-first (id/tool/result_kind/summary); obs_get(id) loads the full payload from CAS. CHECK THIS BEFORE RE-RUNNING a heavy analysis — results persist here, so analyze once and reuse forever; promote only what matters into the graph.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "tool": {"type": "string", "description": "optional filter by the producing tool"}, "kind": {"type": "string", "description": "optional filter by result_kind (decompilation/xrefs/taint/…)"}, "limit": {"type": "integer"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("read", "obs_get", _t.get_observation, "Read ONE Observation in full incl. its complete payload from CAS — reuse a prior decompilation/xref/taint result instead of paying to re-run it. Observations are the substrate (NOT graph nodes); promote the few that matter into the graph deliberately.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"observation_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["observation_id"]}),
    ("read", "obs_search", _t.search_observations, "Search prior Observations (substring over tool/summary/result_kind) across a project or one target — find earlier analysis to reuse before re-running it.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"query": {"type": "string"}, "project_id": {"type": "string"}, "target_id": {"type": "string"}, "limit": {"type": "integer"}}, "required": ["query"]}),

    # ---- graph: the curated node/edge/hypothesis graph ------------------------------
    ("read", "graph_search", _t.search, "Keyword-search the CURATED graph — finding titles and promoted function/node names — to relocate something already in the graph by name. This is one of three searches, each over a different corpus: graph_search (the curated graph, here), obs_search (the raw Observation store of prior tool runs), and re_search_decompiled (the text of decompiled function bodies). Pick by what you're looking for.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "q": {"type": "string", "description": "keyword/substring to match against finding titles + node names"}}, "required": ["project_id", "q"]}),
    ("read", "graph_get_node", _t.get_node, "Read ONE node in full by id — its type, address, and every attr you set (a function's summary/params, a sink's operation/why) — to confirm a graph_create_node landed or inspect a node another agent/task added.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"node_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["node_id"]}),
    ("read", "graph_list_nodes", _t.list_nodes, "List the curated graph's nodes (optionally filtered to one target or one node_type) with their address + attrs — survey what's already promoted before adding more, or look up a node's id to wire an edge to it.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "target_id": {"type": "string", "description": "optional: only this target's nodes"}, "node_type": {"type": "string", "enum": NODE_TYPES, "description": "optional filter by node type"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "graph_list_edges", _t.list_edges, "List the graph's edges (optionally only those touching a given node) with their type + attrs — confirm the dataflow/relationships you wired, or get an edge's id to update or delete it.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "node_id": {"type": "string", "description": "optional: only edges touching this node"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "graph_list_sockets", _t.list_sockets, "List socket endpoints (tcp/udp/unix/…) with who listens/connects on each — the firmware's network map (server↔client over shared sockets).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "graph_list_hypotheses", _t.list_hypotheses, "The project's hypothesis WORKLIST — a row per hypothesis with its statement, evidence status (open/supported/refuted/contested + pinned verdicts), work_state (investigating/parked/done), pinned_to_graph flag, and support/refute counts. Filter by `work_state` and/or evidence `status`. Your 'what am I working on / chasing' orient before recording a new hypothesis or resuming a session; pair with graph_create_hypothesis (add) and graph_close_hypothesis (check off).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "work_state": {"type": "string", "enum": HYPOTHESIS_WORK_STATES, "description": "optional filter: investigating/parked/done"}, "status": {"type": "string", "enum": HYPOTHESIS_STATUSES, "description": "optional filter by evidence verdict"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "graph_stats", _t.graph_stats, "Per-type node/edge TALLIES for the project's live graph (nodes_by_type, edges_by_type, totals + target/finding counts) — get before/after counts to see what a task or your curation added, WITHOUT graph_list_nodes (which truncates at 500 and can't count a large graph). Archived targets/nodes excluded.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_create_node", _t.create_node, "PROMOTE: deliberately add a curated result to the graph as a node. The graph is a curated result set, so add only nodes that carry your reasoning, not the binary's whole structure. ALWAYS pass target_id for target-bound types (else it's an orphan); it auto-links to its target and pulls any waiting always-welcome facts (prototype/address) from prior Observations. Populate `attrs` with the type's recommended fields from meta_get_schemas.node_attribute_schemas (function->summary+params, input->source, sink->operation+why). A dangerous call (system/strcpy) is a symbol/function node with is_sink=true — NOT a separate `sink` node. Pass `address` for code nodes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "node_type": {"type": "string", "enum": NODE_TYPES, "description": "the curated entity's type"}, "name": {"type": "string"}, "target_id": {"type": "string", "description": "REQUIRED for target-bound types, else the node is an orphan"}, "address": {"type": "string", "description": "hex address for code nodes"}, "attrs": {"type": "object", "description": "type-specific attributes (see meta_get_schemas.node_attribute_schemas)"}}, "required": ["project_id", "node_type", "name"]}),
    ("write", "graph_create_edge", _t.create_edge, "Connect two graph entities (target|node|finding|task) with a typed, attributed edge. The required `type` param (NOT `edge_type`) names the relationship — one of the EdgeType vocabulary that meta_get_schemas lists under `edge_types`. `attrs` carries edge-type facts (see meta_get_schemas: e.g. calls→call_sites/arg_constraints, listens_on→address). merge=True accumulates list attrs. A hypothesis is a 'node'; or use graph_link_evidence to attach a finding to one.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "src_kind": {"type": "string", "enum": ["target", "node", "finding", "task"], "description": "source endpoint kind"}, "src_id": {"type": "string"}, "dst_kind": {"type": "string", "enum": ["target", "node", "finding", "task"], "description": "destination endpoint kind"}, "dst_id": {"type": "string"}, "type": {"type": "string", "enum": EDGE_TYPES, "description": "REQUIRED — the edge relationship type, an EdgeType value (the vocab meta_get_schemas reports as `edge_types`). Pass it as `type`, not `edge_type`."}, "attrs": {"type": "object", "description": "edge-type attributes (see meta_get_schemas.edge_attribute_schemas)"}, "merge": {"type": "boolean", "description": "accumulate list attrs instead of replacing"}}, "required": ["project_id", "src_kind", "src_id", "dst_kind", "dst_id", "type"]}),
    ("write", "graph_update_edge", _t.update_edge, "Add/update attributes on an EXISTING edge by id (merge=True accumulates list attrs like call_sites; merge=False replaces). See meta_get_schemas for per-type attributes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"edge_id": {"type": "string"}, "attrs": {"type": "object"}, "merge": {"type": "boolean"}}, "required": ["edge_id", "attrs"]}),
    ("write", "graph_set_node_attr", _t.set_node_attr, "Set ONE attribute on an existing node by id (e.g. is_sink=true, or attrs.entry=true to mark a reachability source) WITHOUT re-sending the whole node via graph_create_node. Sets just `key`; the node's other attrs are untouched. Returns the updated node.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"node_id": {"type": "string"}, "key": {"type": "string", "description": "the attribute name (e.g. is_sink, entry)"}, "value": {"description": "the attribute value (any JSON type — bool/string/number/list/object)"}}, "required": ["node_id", "key", "value"]}),
    ("write", "graph_create_socket", _t.create_socket, "Create/reuse a SOCKET graph NODE (a network/IPC endpoint shared across binaries — NOT a live target; for a fuzzable live service use target_register_service). Give port or name. A server listens_on it, a client connects_to it — both resolve to one node.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "kind": {"type": "string", "enum": SOCKET_KIND_VALUES, "description": "socket kind"}, "port": {"type": ["integer", "string"], "description": "port (give port or name)"}, "name": {"type": "string", "description": "named endpoint (e.g. a unix socket path)"}, "bind_addr": {"type": "string"}, "attrs": {"type": "object"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_create_hypothesis", _t.create_hypothesis, "Record a research hypothesis (a falsifiable open QUESTION you're chasing — NOT a settled fact, which is a node/edge/finding) anchored to a target; it lands on your live worklist as work_state='investigating' and stays OFF the canvas unless pinned. Confirm/refute it by attaching findings with graph_link_evidence, then graph_close_hypothesis when you've settled it. See graph_list_hypotheses for the worklist.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "statement": {"type": "string"}, "rationale": {"type": "string"}, "target_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id", "statement"]}),
    ("write", "graph_link_evidence", _t.link_evidence, "Attach a finding to a hypothesis as supporting/refuting evidence (recomputes the hypothesis status). This is how you confirm a hypothesis.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"hypothesis_id": {"type": "string"}, "finding_id": {"type": "string"}, "relation": {"type": "string", "enum": EVIDENCE_RELATIONS, "description": "does the finding support or refute the hypothesis"}}, "required": ["hypothesis_id", "finding_id", "relation"]}),
    ("write", "graph_set_hypothesis_status", _t.set_hypothesis_status, "Update a hypothesis along EITHER axis (pass at least one): `status` pins the evidence verdict (when you're not driving it through graph_link_evidence); `work_state` moves the orthogonal worklist axis (investigating | parked | done). Pass `rationale` to record why.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"hypothesis_id": {"type": "string"}, "status": {"type": "string", "enum": HYPOTHESIS_STATUSES, "description": "the evidence verdict"}, "work_state": {"type": "string", "enum": HYPOTHESIS_WORK_STATES, "description": "the worklist axis (investigating/parked/done) — orthogonal to status"}, "rationale": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["hypothesis_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_close_hypothesis", _t.close_hypothesis, "CHECK OFF a hypothesis: set work_state='done' and optionally record the evidence `verdict` (confirmed | rejected | supported | refuted | …) for how it resolved — a proven question closes confirmed/supported, a ruled-out one refuted/rejected (a documented dead end). Use when you've settled a hypothesis either way; park (graph_set_hypothesis_status work_state='parked') one you've only set aside.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"hypothesis_id": {"type": "string"}, "verdict": {"type": "string", "enum": HYPOTHESIS_STATUSES, "description": "optional evidence verdict explaining how it closed"}, "rationale": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["hypothesis_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_annotate", _t.annotate, "Attach a note/tag/rename/type_decl to a graph entity (agent PROPOSAL, pending analyst approval). A confirmed `rename` round-trips into the persistent Ghidra project and re-decompiles, so the new name sticks for every future decompile. For parameters/explanations on a function, prefer graph_create_node attrs.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "node_kind": {"type": "string", "enum": ANNOTATION_NODE_KINDS, "description": "the kind of entity being annotated"}, "node_id": {"type": "string"}, "kind": {"type": "string", "enum": ANNOTATION_KINDS, "description": "annotation kind"}, "value": {"type": "string", "description": "the note text / tag / new name / type decl"}}, "required": ["project_id", "node_kind", "node_id", "kind", "value"]}),
    ("write", "graph_merge_duplicates", _t.merge_duplicates, "Fold duplicate nodes/binaries into one canonical node (e.g. the decompiler's `sym.foo` and a hand-added `foo`, or the same binary ingested twice), moving ALL their edges/findings/annotations onto the keeper — nothing is lost. Runs automatically after LLM tasks; call it on demand after you've bulk-added nodes, to de-dup the graph.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_archive_node", _t.archive_node, "Soft-remove a node from the graph (REVERSIBLE): hides the node and the edges touching it. Re-adding the same node (graph_create_node/a task) or graph_restore_node brings it and its edges back — nothing is deleted.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "node_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id", "node_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_restore_node", _t.restore_node, "Un-archive a previously soft-removed node; its hidden edges reappear.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "node_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id", "node_id"]}),
    ("write", "graph_delete_edge", _t.delete_edge, "Permanently delete ONE edge by id (hard delete — recreate with graph_create_edge to restore). To remove a node's edges reversibly, graph_archive_node instead.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"edge_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["edge_id"]}),

    # ---- journal: the freeform research notebook (interpreted narrative) -------------
    ("write", "journal_add", _t.add_journal_entry, "Add an entry to the freeform research JOURNAL — the INTERPRETED-NARRATIVE notebook shared with the human (the idea you had, what you TRIED, what worked/didn't, what you LEARNED), NOT the Observation store (raw tool output — recorded automatically) or findings (substantiated results, finding_record). Always posts as the AGENT (you can't author as the human). Write a short line at each meaningful pivot or dead end and at task close, not one dump at the end. @[label](kind:id) mentions (kind = node|finding|target|hypothesis) become clickable links — mention objects instead of re-describing them. Keep it skimmable.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "body": {"type": "string", "description": "markdown body; @[label](kind:id) to mention a graph object"}, "origin_task_id": {"type": "string", "description": "optional: the task/session this entry came from"}}, "required": ["project_id", "body"]}),
    ("read", "journal_list", _t.list_journal_entries, "List a project's JOURNAL entries (interpreted narrative notes) newest-first, optionally filtered by author — your running log of what you tried and learned, distinct from obs_list (raw tool output) and finding_list (substantiated results). Use to re-orient at the start of a session.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "author": {"type": "string", "enum": JOURNAL_AUTHORS, "description": "optional filter: human | agent"}, "limit": {"type": "integer"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "journal_get", _t.get_journal_entry, "Read ONE journal entry in full, with its @-mentions resolved (a merged/archived target is flagged dangling) — the journal analog of finding_get / graph_get_node.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"entry_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["entry_id"]}),
    ("read", "journal_search", _t.search_journal, "Search the freeform research JOURNAL (interpreted narrative notes) — NOT Observations (raw tool output, obs_search) or findings (finding_list). Substring over entry bodies, newest first. Your highest-value cross-session memory: journal_search('what did I try on the CGI handler') re-orients a fresh session in one call.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"query": {"type": "string"}, "project_id": {"type": "string"}, "limit": {"type": "integer"}}, "required": ["query", "project_id"]}),
    ("write", "journal_update", _t.update_journal_entry, "Edit one of YOUR OWN journal entries by id (refuses a HUMAN-authored entry — the journal is a trust artifact, the human's words stay theirs). Marks the entry edited and re-parses its @-mentions.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"entry_id": {"type": "string"}, "body": {"type": "string", "description": "the new markdown body"}}, "required": ["entry_id", "body"]}),
    ("write", "journal_delete", _t.delete_journal_entry, "Delete one of YOUR OWN journal entries by id (refuses a HUMAN-authored entry). Hard delete — re-add with journal_add if needed.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"entry_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["entry_id"]}),

    # ---- finding: findings, n-day, proving ------------------------------------------
    ("read", "finding_list", _t.list_findings, "Existing findings in a project, NEWEST-FIRST (each row carries finding_type + verified flag + the compact assurance triple). Paginated and filterable. BY DEFAULT excludes the high-volume `recon` findings (ingest mints one per child target — easily hundreds); pass include_recon=true (or finding_type='recon') to include them.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "limit": {"type": "integer", "description": "max rows (default 100; 0 = no limit)"}, "offset": {"type": "integer", "description": "skip this many (for paging, default 0)"}, "finding_type": {"type": "string", "enum": FINDING_TYPE_VALUES, "description": "filter by producing-task class (e.g. vulnerability/fuzz_crash/poc); set 'recon' to see the per-child recon rows"}, "status": {"type": "string", "enum": FINDING_STATUSES, "description": "filter by triage status"}, "severity": {"type": "string", "enum": SEVERITIES, "description": "filter by severity"}, "target_id": {"type": "string", "description": "only findings on this target"}, "verified": {"type": "boolean", "description": "only PoC-verified (true) or only unverified (false) findings; pagination is over the verified-filtered set"}, "include_recon": {"type": "boolean", "description": "include the high-volume recon findings (default false)"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "finding_get", _t.get_finding, "Read ONE finding in full incl. complete evidence (evidence.extra holds the finding_verify_poc result) — confirm a write landed (finding analog of graph_get_node).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"finding_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["finding_id"]}),
    ("write", "finding_record", _t.record_finding, "Record a new finding (the `finding` dict must match the Finding schema — call meta_get_schemas). `finding_type` is a SEPARATE arg, not a finding field. A `cwe` in evidence.extra (e.g. \"CWE-787\") is lifted to a first-class, filterable triage field. Pass task_id in delegate mode.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "target_id": {"type": "string"}, "finding": {"type": "object", "description": "the Finding-schema dict (call meta_get_schemas['finding'] for the full shape)", "properties": {
        "title": {"type": "string", "description": "one-line headline naming the flaw + where"},
        "severity": {"type": "string", "enum": SEVERITIES},
        "confidence": {"type": "string", "enum": CONFIDENCES},
        "category": {"type": "string", "enum": CATEGORIES, "description": "the flaw class (NOT the finding_type arg)"},
        "summary": {"type": "string", "description": "what the flaw is, in a sentence or two"},
        "reasoning": {"type": "string", "description": "why it's a flaw — the analysis, citing the evidence"},
        "evidence": {"type": "object", "description": "function/sink/address/reproducer + extra (assurance, cwe, …); see meta_get_schemas['finding']"},
     }, "required": ["title", "severity", "confidence", "category", "summary", "reasoning", "evidence"]}, "finding_type": {"type": "string", "enum": FINDING_TYPE_VALUES, "description": "the producing-task class (a DB envelope field, not part of the frozen Finding schema)"}, "task_id": {"type": "string", "description": "delegate mode only"}}, "required": ["project_id", "target_id", "finding"]}),
    ("write", "finding_update", _t.update_finding, "Update an EXISTING finding in place (status/severity/confidence/human_notes/cwe) — e.g. confirm it after a PoC verifies, or set/correct the triage CWE. Don't create a duplicate.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"finding_id": {"type": "string"}, "status": {"type": "string", "enum": FINDING_STATUSES, "description": "triage status"}, "severity": {"type": "string", "enum": SEVERITIES}, "confidence": {"type": "string", "enum": CONFIDENCES}, "human_notes": {"type": "string"}, "cwe": {"type": "string", "description": "CWE id (e.g. CWE-787 or 787) — normalized to CWE-<n>"}}, "required": ["finding_id"]}),
    ("write", "finding_delete", _t.delete_finding, "Permanently DELETE a junk finding by id (hard delete — IRREVERSIBLE; also removes every edge/annotation touching it). Use only for pure noise. To set a finding aside reversibly instead (keep the row, greyed, restorable), call finding_update(status='dismissed').",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"finding_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["finding_id"]}),
    ("write", "finding_link_to_source", _t.link_finding_to_source, "Link a finding to its location in a managed source file (a `located_in` edge + evidence.extra.source_ref) — the jump-from-finding-to-source link. tree_id/rel from src_list_trees/src_read_file; pass `line` to scroll there. Use when a vuln/harness corresponds to known source.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"finding_id": {"type": "string"}, "tree_id": {"type": "string"}, "rel": {"type": "string", "description": "file path within the source tree"}, "line": {"type": "integer"}, "col": {"type": "integer"}}, "required": ["finding_id", "tree_id", "rel"]}),
    ("write", "finding_link_same_code", _t.link_same_code, "Cross-target n-day primitive (bindiff/similarity): link functions with identical code (same content_hash) across DIFFERENT binaries via similar_to edges, and return the matches (each side flags has_findings). Run after confirming a bug to find the same routine reused elsewhere, then finding_propagate.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("write", "finding_propagate", _t.propagate_finding, "N-day: clone an existing finding onto another binary that shares the same code (per finding_link_same_code) as a fresh finding to triage, wired derived_from→ the source. Avoids re-typing the whole finding for 'same bug, other binary'.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"finding_id": {"type": "string"}, "target_id": {"type": "string"}, "function": {"type": "string"}, "notes": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["finding_id", "target_id"]}),
    ("run", "finding_reachability", _t.reachability, "Argue STATIC input-reachability (Standard B, static): search the typed graph for a directed source→sink path so a finding can claim input_reachable/static even when you CAN'T trigger it live (a real sink, but the service won't boot — the DIR-823G case). Pass finding_id (resolves the sink it cites, RECORDS the path + upgraded assurance on the finding) and/or sink_node_id (reports a path to that sink). Sources = input/param/endpoint/socket nodes (or a function/symbol you marked attrs.entry); follows taints/calls/routes_to/reads/writes/references FORWARD (taints is the strongest signal), depth-bounded + cycle-safe. Precondition is derived from the path (crosses an auth boundary / a `bypasses` edge => requires_credentials; starts at an unauth boundary => unauthenticated; else unspecified) — OR pass `precondition` to ASSERT it yourself (e.g. `unauthenticated` when the route is pre-auth but the graph lacks the auth markers, so the inferred default would under-state it); a caller-asserted precondition is recorded as NOT inferred. An ARGUMENT, not a trigger — it only UPGRADES a code_present/static floor and NEVER downgrades a dynamic claim. Build the input/sink nodes + taints/calls edges first.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"finding_id": {"type": "string"}, "sink_node_id": {"type": "string"}, "max_depth": {"type": "integer"}, "precondition": {"type": "string", "enum": REACHABILITY_PRECONDITIONS, "description": "OVERRIDE the path-derived precondition (assert the principal the claim requires)"}}, "required": []}),
    ("run", "finding_verify_poc", _t.verify_poc, "Prove an exploit and report verified true/false (the gold bar). Binary target -> runs it in the sandbox (spec {argv?,argv_b64?,env?,stdin?,stdin_b64?,oracle:{output_contains|exit_code|crash}}, needs features.poc). For RAW-BYTE input (a non-printable argv serial like 0x3b25065c4b20040f, or binary stdin) use argv_b64 (list of base64'd elements, exec'd as raw bytes) / stdin_b64 instead of argv/stdin, which str()-mangle non-printable bytes. SOLVER HANDOFF: to verify an angr-solver finding's reproducer byte-faithfully, pass finding_id=<that finding> with poc={oracle:{…}} and NO argv/stdin — HexGraph fills argv_b64/stdin_b64 from evidence.extra.solver. Web surface -> sends HTTP steps (spec {steps:[{method,path,body?,...}],oracle:{body_contains|status_is|status_differs}}, cookies carry across steps for auth flows, needs features.network). Raw TCP service -> spec {transport:'tcp', port, payload, oracle:{response_contains}} (needs features.network); use for a rehosted/remote device's non-HTTP daemon. Raw UDP service -> spec {transport:'udp', port, payload, oracle:{response_contains}} (needs features.network); the datagram analogue, for a UDP daemon (infosvr/SSDP/mDNS/DNS/DHCP). Put {{NONCE}} in BOTH the payload and the oracle value for an unforgeable check. Extra oracles prove vuln classes BEYOND reflected cmdi by observing an INDEPENDENT channel (call meta_get_schemas['verify_poc_oracles'] for the spec): blind cmdi/SSRF/blind RCE -> oracle {type:'callback'} + a {{CALLBACK}} token (the target dials a bounded local listener); arbitrary READ (traversal/disclosure) -> {plant:{channel:'rootfs',path}|{known_value}} + oracle {type:'canary_read'}; arbitrary WRITE (file/config/NVRAM) -> write {{NONCE}} then oracle {type:'oob_write', channel:'rootfs'|'remote'|'http', path?|request?}; DENIAL OF SERVICE of a live web/TCP service -> oracle {type:'liveness', reprobes?, port?}. Pass finding_id to attach the result (always do this for a confirmed vuln). Gated: features.poc (binary) / features.network (web/tcp).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "poc": {"type": "object", "description": "the self-contained PoC spec (argv/argv_b64/steps/payload + oracle; use {{NONCE}}/{{CALLBACK}}/{{CANARY}}; argv_b64/stdin_b64 carry RAW BYTES base64'd for non-printable input)"}, "finding_id": {"type": "string", "description": "attach the verification result to this finding (always do this for a confirmed vuln); for an angr-solver finding, the recovered argv/stdin is filled in byte-faithfully when the spec omits its own input"}}, "required": ["target_id", "poc"]}),

    # ---- src: source trees + builds -------------------------------------------------
    ("read", "src_list_trees", _t.list_source_trees, "List the project's managed SOURCE trees (trusted source we possess/build — NOT the hostile target). Harnesses, PoCs, and build/run scripts live here as role-tagged source_files. Returns id/name/origin/file_count + which targets are built_from each. Use src_read_file to view a tree's files.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "src_read_file", _t.read_source_file, "Browse/read a managed SOURCE tree (tree_id from src_list_trees). Omit `rel` to LIST files (rel/size/role); pass `rel` to READ one file's text (bounded, traversal-safe; binary as hex). Trusted source text (a harness/PoC/build recipe / imported library source) — distinct from fs_read_file, which reads a firmware's hostile unpacked bytes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"tree_id": {"type": "string"}, "rel": {"type": "string", "description": "file path within the tree; omit to LIST files"}}, "required": ["tree_id"]}),
    ("read", "src_list_builds", _t.list_builds, "List builds in a project — the build ledger. Each carries status, the reproducibility triple (recipe_sha/source_content_hash/toolchain_digest), artifacts as CAS shas, and the instrumented derived_target_id it registered. Optionally filter by source_tree_id. Returns {build_specs, builds}.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "source_tree_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id"]}),
    ("read", "src_build_log", _t.build_log, "The full build log (stdout+stderr of every phase, from CAS) for a build — the recipe-iteration signal on a FAILED build. Read it to see WHY a compile/instrumentation step failed (missing header, a flag the sanitizer rejected, a cross-compile sysroot miss), fix phases/env/arch, and rebuild. build_id from src_list_builds. Returns {build_id, status, returncode, error, log}.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"build_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["build_id"]}),
    ("write", "src_import_tree", _t.import_source_tree, "Create a managed SOURCE tree and optionally populate it. `files` = [{rel,content,role?}]. Use to bring in a harness/PoC you authored or a small library's source. Trusted text only — NOT target bytes (those are target_ingest'd as targets). Returns {id,name,written}.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "name": {"type": "string"}, "files": {"type": "array", "description": "[{rel, content, role?}] — role one of " + "/".join(SOURCE_ROLES)}, "origin": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["project_id", "name"]}),
    ("write", "src_save_revision", _t.save_source_revision, "Edit a HexGraph-AUTHORED source file (a harness/PoC/script you wrote) and save it as a NEW REVISION — never an in-place mutation, so the edit is durable + reversible and you can rebuild-from-revision (pass the returned revision id as src_build's source_revision_id). Scratch/HexGraph-authored trees are editable by default; editing OTHER authored trees needs features.source.edit. ALWAYS REFUSES an imported/extracted/vendor (read-only) tree — editing those would break the build content_hash contract. Returns {id, seq, rel, role}. Use to iterate on a harness/PoC in place rather than re-importing.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"tree_id": {"type": "string"}, "rel": {"type": "string"}, "content": {"type": "string"}, "role": {"type": "string", "enum": SOURCE_ROLES}, "note": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["tree_id", "rel", "content"]}),
    ("write", "src_import_oss_fuzz", _t.import_oss_fuzz, "Import an OSS-Fuzz-style `build.sh` into a recorded build_spec so an existing OSS-Fuzz target builds in HexGraph with minimal hand-authoring. The script is stored in the (EDITABLE) tree as role=script; HexGraph maps the OSS-Fuzz env contract ($CC/$CXX/$CFLAGS/$LIB_FUZZING_ENGINE/$SRC/$OUT) to ours, so the script runs essentially unchanged, and auto-detects the $OUT/<name> fuzz targets to capture. Returns the build_spec; then src_build runs it. Bring in the source tree first (src_import_tree).",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "source_tree_id": {"type": "string"}, "build_sh": {"type": "string"}, "instrumentation": {"type": "object"}, "artifacts": {"type": "array"}}, "required": ["project_id", "source_tree_id", "build_sh"]}),
    ("run", "src_build", _t.build_target, "Build a managed SOURCE tree into an INSTRUMENTED artifact in the sandbox via a RECORDED, REPRODUCIBLE recipe (build-as-API): you author/approve a BuildSpec and REQUEST the build — you never run a compiler, HexGraph runs the recipe. `system` (auto-detected if omitted), `phases` (recorded verbatim), `instrumentation` ({sanitizers, coverage:[sancov|afl_pcguard], engine:libfuzzer|afl}), `artifacts` (rel paths to capture), `env` (NON-secret — secrets rejected). Instrumentation is INJECTED as CC/CXX/CFLAGS (base-image contract), so the SAME phases yield ASan/SanCov/AFL++ by swapping the profile. CROSS-COMPILE: pass `arch` to cross-build for a firmware's arch — HexGraph injects clang --target + the parent firmware's extracted rootfs as --sysroot (a cross-build failure degrades to qemu-mode binary-only fuzzing). DEPENDENCIES: `network` defaults 'none' (vendored/offline, fully reproducible); 'fetch' (requires features.build_fetch) runs a SEPARATE, audited, ALLOWLISTED fetch phase (`fetch_phases`) that hash-pins deps into a LOCKFILE, then DROPS NETWORK and compiles --network none; the build records a lockfile + SBOM-lite + a reproducibility BADGE, and a cache HIT REUSES the prior artifact. `source_revision_id` builds from a specific editable-IDE revision. If the tree is built_from a target, the rebuild registers a DERIVED target wired instrumented_build_of→ the original. Gated: features.build.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}, "source_tree_id": {"type": "string"}, "system": {"type": "string", "enum": BUILD_SYSTEMS, "description": "build system (auto-detected if omitted)"}, "phases": {"type": "array", "description": "shell phases, recorded verbatim"}, "instrumentation": {"type": "object", "description": "{sanitizers, coverage, engine} — injected via CC/CXX/CFLAGS"}, "artifacts": {"type": "array", "description": "rel paths of build outputs to capture"}, "env": {"type": "object", "description": "NON-secret build env (secrets rejected)"}, "arch": {"type": "string", "enum": ["mips", "mipsel", "arm", "armhf", "aarch64"], "description": "cross-compile target arch (matches the firmware userland)"}, "network": {"type": "string", "enum": ["none", "fetch"], "description": "dep policy (default none; fetch needs features.build_fetch)"}, "fetch_phases": {"type": "array"}, "source_revision_id": {"type": "string", "description": "build from a specific src_save_revision revision"}}, "required": ["project_id", "source_tree_id"]}),

    # ---- fuzz: campaigns, artifacts, environments, coverage -------------------------
    ("read", "fuzz_status", _t.fuzz_status, "Live status + stats of a fuzz CAMPAIGN (status, execs, edges_covered, crash_count, coverage). Reaps on read so figures are fresh. Poll this while a campaign runs — crashes stream to fuzz_crash findings as they happen, so an early crash in a long campaign surfaces within minutes.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"campaign_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["campaign_id"]}),
    ("read", "fuzz_list_artifacts", _t.list_fuzz_artifacts, "List a campaign's DEDUPLICATED artifacts (crash/hang/leak/oom/corpus) — each with the normalized dedup_key (one representative per stack-hash bucket + dupe_count), the sanitizer crash kind, the faulting function, the deterministic exploitability rating, the CAS reproducer sha (re-runnable via finding_verify_poc / fuzz_minimize_artifact), and the fuzz_crash finding it produced.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"campaign_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["campaign_id"]}),
    ("read", "fuzz_list_environments", _t.list_fuzz_environments, "List registered fuzz ENVIRONMENTS — where a campaign's container can run: `local` (the host Docker daemon) + N user-owned remote Docker hosts (beefier/unconstrained compute). Each carries the non-secret label/descriptor, the ResourceSpec ceiling, presence-only `connection_present` (the secret DOCKER_HOST/creds live in env/config.toml, never stored/returned), and the cached health-check. Pass an environment id to fuzz_start's `environment` arg to run a campaign there — building + fuzzing run on the remote with NO analysis change, the SAME sandbox boundary. Gated: features.fuzz_remote.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"project_id": {"type": "string"}}}),
    ("read", "fuzz_environment_health", _t.fuzz_environment_health, "Health-check a remote fuzz environment: is it reachable + authorized + does it have the fuzz image present (the one-time remote build/pull)? Returns a NON-SECRET {ok, reachable, authorized, image_present, docker_version, detail} — the connection string is never echoed. Gated: features.fuzz_remote.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"environment_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["environment_id"]}),
    ("read", "fuzz_coverage_diff", _t.coverage_diff, "Run-to-run COVERAGE DIFF between two fuzz campaigns: what NEW source lines did `other_campaign_id` reach that `campaign_id` (the base) did not (and which did it lose)? The 'did this run reach new edges?' answer — use to judge whether a harness/corpus/engine change actually improved reach. Returns per-file {gained, lost} + project totals; available=False when either campaign exposed no per-line coverage map.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"campaign_id": {"type": "string"}, "other_campaign_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["campaign_id", "other_campaign_id"]}),
    ("run", "fuzz_start", _t.start_fuzz_campaign, "Start a multi-surface fuzz CAMPAIGN on a target; returns immediately with {id, status:'running'}. You REQUEST it — you NEVER run a fuzzer; HexGraph spawns a DETACHED, hardened sandbox container and a reaper streams each unique crash → a fuzz_crash finding with a one-click-re-verifiable reproducer (via fuzz_verify_artifact). `surface` auto-infers from the target (override surface/engine, validated fail-closed): source_lib (an INSTRUMENTED derived target, with source) → AFL++ coverage-guided; binary_only (a stripped firmware ELF, NO source) → AFL++ qemu-mode (engine='qemu' default; engine='frida' alt; foreign-arch MIPS/ARM runs under qemu-user + the parent firmware rootfs as sysroot); network (a LIVE service) → boofuzz (engine='boofuzz' default — pass host/port/proto_spec if not on the target; a crash = service death = input_reachable/dynamic, the strongest assurance) or engine='desock' (coverage-fuzz a LOCAL server binary with --network none). file_format → AFL++ + auto-dictionary. `instances` = AFL++ master + N-1 secondaries. `resources` = a ResourceSpec override; `unconstrained` lifts mem/cpu/pids ONLY (the sandbox security flags always hold). `environment` selects WHERE the container runs (fuzz_list_environments): omit/'local' for the host daemon, or a registered remote Docker host. Optional `seeds`/`dictionary` shape the search; `max_len` caps input size. Source-fuzz instrumentation knobs (each defaults to its features.fuzzing.* setting): `bug_oracles` (AFL++ 5.x SCALAR/BUDGET/SIZEFILL/ALLOCSIZE/SLACK detectors), `path_coverage` 0-3 (Ball-Larus path sensitivity), `cmplog` (magic-byte/memcmp gating). Then poll fuzz_status + read fuzz_list_artifacts. Gated by surface: source/binary-only/desock need features.fuzzing (or features.poc); a LIVE-socket boofuzz campaign needs features.network; a remote environment needs features.fuzz_remote.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"target_id": {"type": "string"}, "surface": {"type": "string", "enum": FUZZ_SURFACES, "description": "attack surface (auto-inferred from the target if omitted)"}, "engine": {"type": "string", "enum": FUZZ_ENGINES, "description": "fuzz engine (surface-defaulted if omitted)"}, "function": {"type": "string"}, "max_total_time": {"type": "integer", "description": "campaign budget seconds"}, "max_len": {"type": "integer", "description": "max input length (coverage-guided)"}, "max_crashes": {"type": "integer"}, "instances": {"type": "integer", "description": "AFL++ master + N-1 secondaries"}, "seeds": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}, "description": "host seed-corpus file paths (optional)"}, "dictionary": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}, "description": "fuzzing dictionary tokens (optional; auto-derived from the target's strings when omitted)"}, "host": {"type": "string", "description": "network surface: the live service host (loopback/private only); inferred from a rehosted/web target when omitted"}, "port": {"type": "integer", "description": "network surface: the service port; inferred from the target when omitted"}, "protocol": {"type": "string", "enum": ["tcp", "udp"], "description": "network surface: transport for boofuzz (default tcp)"}, "proto_spec": {"type": "object", "description": "network surface: the boofuzz generational request/state spec for a binary protocol"}, "launch": {"type": "boolean", "description": "network surface (launch-and-join): force HexGraph to START the service itself and join the fuzzer to its netns"}, "launch_binary": {"type": "string", "description": "network surface (launch-and-join): the server ELF path to launch"}, "launch_command": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}, "description": "network surface (launch-and-join): the FULL argv the launched server needs to stay foreground and bind its port, e.g. [\"-f\", \"-p\", \"9999\"] (each element ONE argv token — not a space-joined string)"}, "bug_oracles": {"type": "boolean", "description": "source-fuzz: enable AFL++ 5.x bug-detection oracles (SCALAR/BUDGET/SIZEFILL/ALLOCSIZE/SLACK — catches arithmetic/OOB bugs ASan misses); defaults to features.fuzzing.bug_oracles"}, "path_coverage": {"type": "integer", "enum": [0, 1, 2, 3], "description": "source-fuzz: Ball-Larus per-function path coverage — 0=off, 1=relaxed, 2=restricted, 3=strict (more signal, more overhead); defaults to features.fuzzing.path_coverage"}, "cmplog": {"type": "boolean", "description": "source-fuzz: build the CmpLog -c binary to defeat magic-byte/memcmp gates; defaults to features.fuzzing.cmplog"}, "resources": {"type": "object", "description": "ResourceSpec override {mem,cpus,pids,tmpfs,timeout,unconstrained}"}, "environment": {"type": "string", "description": "fuzz environment id (fuzz_list_environments); omit for local"}}, "required": ["target_id"]}),
    ("run", "fuzz_stop", _t.stop_fuzz_campaign, "Stop a running fuzz campaign — kills the detached container PRESERVING the corpus in CAS (resumable via fuzz_resume), after reaping any final crashes so nothing is lost.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"campaign_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["campaign_id"]}),
    ("run", "fuzz_resume", _t.resume_fuzz_campaign, "Resume a FINISHED fuzz campaign (stopped/completed/failed/degraded), re-seeded from its preserved CAS corpus so it continues accumulating coverage + crashes instead of starting cold — the other half of fuzz_stop's 'resumable'. AFL++ resumes natively. The surface-correct policy gate is re-applied inside — NO new gate. Returns the campaign dict; poll fuzz_status as before.",
     {"type": "object", "properties": {"campaign_id": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["campaign_id"]}),
